The paper deals with a new algorithm for probability forecasting of binary observations, which is a common problem in machine learning and statistics. The paper does not focus on any specific application area, but rather on the theoretical properties of the algorithm. Therefore, it is likely to be relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, such as machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), statistics (cs.ST), information theory (cs.IT), and social and information networks (cs.SI).
